Introduction of the Committee  
The Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) is one of the main organs of  
the United Nations (UN), which aims to foster sustainable development on  
various aspects inclusive of economics, social, and environment. ECOSOC  
also creates forums to enable governments to discuss the solution to global  
challenges and the facilitation of the integration of three previously  
mentioned key factors. Through collective efforts, Member States are  
easier to reach consensus and strengthen intergovernmental partnerships.  
Recently, ECOSOC is putting efforts into the advocacy and implementation  
of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) in order to build a more  
concrete but considerate world as well as all human beings.  
Introduction of the topic  
The history of mankind has been plagued with disease and pandemic. With  
its progression into the modern world, new challenges have arisen and lead  
to even more catastrophic events. It has been brought to notice that the  
most recent pandemic, coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19), has  
enhanced the current inequalities already existing in society, allowing the  
already dire situation to escalate. Given the global demographics of the  
world at large, these socially vulnerable groups have been even more  
prone to the effects of these pandemics and also pose a threat to the many  
Sustainable Development Goals by the UN. Specific goals have been  
affected such as education and decent work have faced the most impact  
under the given circumstances.  
The aim of this committee would be for delegates to establish a plan  
and debate on solutions on how to engage in the goals of the UN  
SDGs amidst the pandemic and ensure that minorities get the aid they  
need. T his background guide will provide sufficient details and information  
on the UNs Sustainable Development Goals and past pandemic related  
solutions and history by the UN and its organs. Delegates will be required  
to have a solid understanding of the topic, be able to come up with  
solutions according to your extensive research on your country's stances,  
and most of all, be open to collaboration with other delegates.  
Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs)  
Overview  
The Sustainable Development Goals were 17 goals set by the UN General  
Assembly in hopes of solving the many global challenges we face.  
According to the UNs website, the SDGs were quoted as The blueprint to  
achieve a better and more sustainable future for all. The UN set these  
goals in motion in 2015 and expects to complete them in 2030 in a  
resolution known as the Resolution of 2030. These 17 goals cover many  
aspects and different challenges internationally, these SDGs are also broad  
and interdependent. Each of which has a list of specific targets that are  
aimed to accomplish, thus indicators and standards are given so progress  
can be tracked and results can be held accountable. In this conference, we  
will be specifying on goals that highly relate to capacity strengthening,  
which is goal 4 and goal 8, quality education and decent working and  
economic growth respectively. In the following section, we will lay  
emphasis on both goals.  
SDG No.4  
Goal 4 of the Sustainable Development Goals is titled Quality Education,  
its statement being Ensure inclusive and equitable quality education and  
promote lifelong learning opportunities for all. SDG No.4 has 10 goals with  
11 indicators that track its process. Certain goals would have been  
impacted the most due to a pandemic, which are as follows:  
Goal 4.1: By 2030, ensure that all girls and boys complete free, equitable and quality  
primary and secondary education leading to relevant and effective learning outcomes  
Goal 4.2: By 2030, ensure that all girls and boys have access to quality early childhood  
development, care and pre-primary education so that they are ready for primary  
education  
Goal 4.3: By 2030, ensure equal access for all women and men to affordable and  
quality technical, vocational and tertiary education, including university  
Goal 4.4: By 2030, substantially increase the number of youth and adults who have  
relevant skills, including technical and vocational skills, for employment, decent jobs and  
entrepreneurship  
Goal 4.5: By 2030, ensure that all learners acquire the knowledge and skills needed to  
promote sustainable development, including, among others, through education for  
sustainable development and sustainable lifestyles, human rights, gender equality,  
promotion of a culture of peace and non-violence, global citizenship and appreciation of  
cultural diversity and of cultures contribution to sustainable development  
Goal 4.a: Build and upgrade education facilities that are child, disability and gender  
sensitive and provide safe, non-violent, inclusive and effective learning environments for  
all  
The COVID-19 pandemic has notably put almost the entire world into a  
near shutdown in order to contain the virus by limiting its spread. Many  
students worldwide have had to enter quarantine while education institutes  
closed. With the sudden existence of the pandemic that caused such  
measures to be implemented, many students lost the chance to carry on  
their basic education. The progress of UN SDG No.4 has a significant  
stepback and has ever since escalated due to the pandemic situation  
showing less to none signs of slowing down.  
Education enables upward socioeconomic mobility and also plays a key  
role in escaping poverty. Over the past decade, major progress was made  
towards increasing access to education and school enrollment rates at all  
levels, particularly for females. Nevertheless, about 260 million children  
were still out of school in 2018 nearly one-fifth of the global population in  
that age group. And more than half of all children and adolescents  
worldwide are not meeting minimum proficiency standards in reading and  
mathematics.

The economic development has also been impacted severely. With the  
stock market along with an aggregate recession of the economy and other  
many economic phenomena, it can be inferred that the world economy at  
large has entered s tagflation . Unemployment and other social issues have  
been prominent especially under the pandemic. SDG No.8 as a whole is  
one of the most impacted aspects during the pandemic and should be  
strongly focused on.  
COVID-19 has disrupted billions of lives and endangered the global  
economy. The International Monetary Fund (IMF) expects a global  
recession worse than the financial crisis in 2009. As job losses escalate,  
the International Labor Organization (ILO) estimates that nearly half of the  
global workforce is at risk of losing their livelihoods.  
Even before the outbreak of COVID-19, one in five countries home to  
billions of people living in poverty were likely to see per capita incomes  
stagnate or decline in 2020. Now, the economic and financial shocks  
associated with COVID-19such as disruptions to industrial production,  
falling commodity prices, financial market volatility, and rising  
insecurityare derailing the already tepid economic growth and  
compounding heightened risks from other factors.  
Key Actors  
Peoples Republic of China (PRC)  
The COVID-19 pandemic was the very plague that came near in the vicinity  
to the Black Death during the middle ages in modern times. It is claimed  
to have originated from the city of Wuhan, China and quickly spread all  
over the globe which led to a pandemic induced crisis worldwide. This has  
come to show that the nation has first-hand experience with pandemics.  
Despite being accused and speculated of retaining information regarding  
the virus in its initial stages, China has been able to steadily recover  
through a centralized government system. Such was when cities quickly  
underwent lockdown and strict control of personnel location, the  
government was quick on its feet to contain the virus. Chinas student  
population outranks many nations and has been greatly affected. The  
PRCs Ministry of Education had set up its own preventive and alternative  
methods to regain education to keep going. To boost the Economy,  
People's Bank of PRC Launched 1.2 trillion Yuan of the public market  
reverse repurchase operation on February 3rd: Maintain the liquidity of the  
banking system in the special period of epidemic prevention and control,  
meet the reasonable financing needs of the market, reduce the reverse  
repurchase rate by 10 basis points, and provide targeted low-cost special  
re-loan fund.  
Recently, the Chinese economy is experiencing a steady recovery scene  
from the outbreak of the virus. The Economists estimate PRC's yearly GDP  
growth could be north of 2.5% this year even as the rest of the world  
economy is expected to shrink by at least 4%.  
European Union (EU)  
In January 2020, the World Health Organization (WHO) warned the  
European Union of the serious condition. Spain, France, and the United  
Kingdom are the worst-hit areas in Europe. Speaking of economics, a  
large number of workers are unemployed, industry and commerce have  
stagnated, and the stock market has fallen or collapsed.  
The unemployment rate of the workforce under the age of 25 in the  
Eurozone rose from 15.1% in March to 15.8% in April. The EU even stated  
that next year's economic growth is expected to be slightly lower than  
previously expected, and GDP will grow by 5.8% by 2021. The outlook for  
the 19 countries or regions that use the euro has also been reduced, and it  
is expected to shrink to a decline of 8.7% in 2020, which is a full  
percentage point lower than the previous forecast.  
The education sector at the start of the pandemic had been impacted  
severely and entered a recession. At the same time, advanced distance  
education has restricted the teaching ability of people with poorer economic  
conditions. On 7/21, the European Union established a 750 billion euro  
revitalization fund to deal with the economic impact of COVID-19. The  
revitalization plan consists of two parts: 390 billion euros are subsidies that  
do not need to be repaid; the other 360 billion euros are loans that must be  
repaid by the state. It is expected that the funds will be obtained from the  
financial market in the form of collective loans, and the full loan would be  
repaid by 2058. The purposes of the expenses applied for by the  
revitalization fund will be used by each country on its own, including  
economics, medical care, education, etc. The plan helps people keep  
working during the crisis and provides concessional loans to member  
states. Also, these funds will be used to cover some of the costs associated  
with establishing or extending the national short-term work plan, increasing  
employment rates as well as appropriating more educational subsidies.  
United States of America (USA)  
The coronavirus crisis in the United Statesand the associated business  
closures, event cancellations, and work-from-home policieshas triggered  
a deep economic downturn of uncertain duration. The Federal  
Reserve(FED) has stepped in with a broad array of actions to limit the  
economic damage from the pandemic, including up to $2.3 trillion in lending  
to support households, employers, financial markets, and state and local  
governments. The FED is trying to ensure that credit continues to flow to  
households and businesses during this difficult time and that the financial  
system did not amplify the shock to the economy. It is working on limiting  
the permanent damage to the economy so that when the pandemic  
recedes, the economy can grow again, and supply goods and services to  
meet demand.  
The United States Department of Education outlines a three-stage  
response to the affected educational system. The first stage is the  
immediate relief for students and educators. The second stage is significant  
short-term investments during the recovery that will enable students whose  
education was interrupted by the coronavirus crisis to catch up and  
continue their development. The third stage is longer-term reforms to  
rebuild the education system so that the challenges documented here are  
corrected and the system finally delivers an excellent, equitable education  
to all children.  
Cambodia  
Cambodia's ability to survive the economic fallout of the Coronavirus  
Disease 2019 pandemic will be determined by how rapidly it can come to  
the assistance of its poorest and most vulnerable citizens. COVID-19 has  
highlighted glaring vulnerabilities in the structures that have helped to bring  
about a 7% average annual growth in the economy for almost a decade.  
This year, Cambodia faces its worst economic performance since 1994.  
The government is already preparing a long-term strategy for the digital  
economy, which needs to target closing the digital divide and boosting an  
inclusive digital transformation in the wake of economic losses from  
COVID-19. The development and implementation of this new policy  
framework need much more emphasis now. Facilitate digital infrastructure  
development to enable the most vulnerable groups to take part in the digital  
economy. In response to the pandemic, businesses are increasingly  
shifting online, people are being asked to work from home and there is a  
rise in e-commerce activities and digital work all of which is placing  
pressure on existing digital infrastructure. Targeted policies are required for  
digital infrastructure development during the crisis. For instance, Cambodia  
has very low fixed-broadband penetration and low mobile broadband  
penetration compared with other Asian economies, and its market is  
currently dominated by low-quality residential broadband services.  
Targeted support is also required to ensure that those who lose out from  
new technologies in industries can take part elsewhere in the economy.  
This could take the form of rolling out digital infrastructure to those who  
need it most or raising digital literacy in vulnerable groupings.  
The COVID-19 pandemic has forced 810 million children out of schools  
worldwide. Cambodian children are facing the same reality. All of  
Cambodias 13,300 schools have been closed since March 16th, leading  
many children and families to seek distance learning opportunities to  
continue their education.  
To respond to this education crisis, the United Nations Children's Fund  
UNICEF) is working closely with the Ministry of Education, and MoEYS to  
(
establish continuous learning activities from early childhood through to  
primary, lower, and upper secondary education. Distance learning assets,  
including videos and e-lessons, are being broadcast through various social  
media platforms, TV, and radio, aiming to reach every household in  
Cambodia. For UNICEF, one of the key concerns has been to ensure that  
no child is left behind - that every child, despite their ability, gender,  
socio-economic, or ethnic background has access to learning opportunities.  
Libya  
The health and safety of the people across Syria are at risk. Since the  
Lybia war had been triggered nine years ago, nearly 400,000 Libyans have  
been displaced. In the past year, the United Nations has confirmed 113  
serious incidents, including the attacks on schools and health care facilities.  
Hospitals and health facilities have become targets of shelling, further  
disrupting Libyas fragile health systems. Since the beginning of this year,  
at least 15 attacks have damaged health care facilities and ambulances  
and injured health care workers. These attacks blatantly violated  
international humanitarian law and were even heinous during the  
COVID-19 pandemic.  
Food security is already facing challenges, but it is now being further  
expanded by the spread of COVID-19 and its socio-economic impact on  
Libyan families. Most cities are facing shortages of basic food and rising  
prices. Market supplies are limited, inflation and supply chain disruption are  
affecting its delivery. The authorities concerned are obliged to support the  
countrys domestic food security in order to prevent this health crisis  
worsening to a famine.  
The UN supports the National Centre for Disease Control and compliments  
the Libyans' National Response Plan to actively engage and respond to the  
prevention and response of the virus. WHO, the health authorities and  
health partners prioritized six technical areas for urgent support, including  
enhancing surveillance, strengthening rapid response teams; supporting  
health control offices at points of entry; improving laboratory capacity;  
increasing health information and communication; and supporting the  
establishment of isolation wards in selected hospitals and quarantine areas  
at points of entry.

Afghanistan is relevantly vulnerable because of its limited health care system  
and few medical personnel, weak infrastructure, and poor social cohesion  
after 40 years of war, along with a large influx of refugees returning from Iran  
and Pakistanwithout proper quarantine and containment measures in place.  
The government also lacks spending capital to stem the spread of the  
pandemic.

Case Study  
Ebola Virus  
Ebola virus disease (EVD) is a deadly disease with occasional outbreaks  
that plagued Africa. The disease often comes along with severe symptoms  
such as serious headaches, abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomit, and bleeding.  
Compared with other infectious diseases that lead to dramatic pandemics,  
EVD is considered rare but fatal, with a 50 percent average mortality rate.  
The difficulties of LEDCs can be acknowledged by noticing the statistics of  
the EVD outbreak in West Africa during 2014:  
Table 1: the number of cases in highly-infected countries during the 2014 ebola outbreak  
Since the very first case was discovered in rural Guinea in December 2013,  
the disease rapidly spread over the region and some of its nearby  
countries, Liberia and Sierra Leone while infecting thousands of people and  
taking over 10000 lives away. According to the analysis made by the U.S.  
Department of Health and Human Services, weak surveillance systems and  
poor public health infrastructures are the two primary culprits of this  
massive outbreak. Its also of note that the outbreak in 2014 was also the  
time that E VD has disseminated from rural areas into densely populated  
places, providing an opportunity for viruses to transmit.)  
After the outbreak, several measures were taken by separate governments  
or international communities to help mitigate the situation. To be specific,  
engaging local leaders in prevention programs and establish  
cross-governmental dialogues, along with careful policy implementation at  
the national and global level, helped to eventually contain the spread of the  
virus and put an end to this outbreak. Also, several laboratories for  
ebolavirus testing were established shortly after the end of the pandemic,  
and the WHO started to send experts to places at which show signs of a  
possible outbreak. In conclusion, these improvements can only be done by  
raising the awareness of governments in countries involved in order to  
receive decent help from the international community.  
SARS  
Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome, commonly known as SARS, was a  
disease caused by the coronavirus and thus ended up becoming a  
pandemic in 2003. SARS was first discovered in Guangdong, PRC. Soon  
after, the disease has rapidly spread to many regions in Eastern Asia,  
including Hong Kong, Singapore, and Taiwan.  
Figure1: Number of SARS cases  
Although SARS brought chaos to public health, it provided a paradigm in  
how pandemics affect the global economy, as globalization has become an  
unstoppable trend. There were a lot of discussions and predictions about  
the financial impact resulting from the pandemic, some were accurate while  
some were eventually proved wrong. As time goes by, we can now take a  
closer look at how things turned out to be. To begin with, all kinds of  
business, tourism, restaurants, accommodations, and food services are the  
most-damaged industries. It is easy to understand since governments  
discourage or even ban people gathering in public places. Also, economic  
decay was more significant in countries with more confirmed cases or  
deaths. Take the two highest-infected countries for instance, Hong Kong  
came across a 3.7 percent declination in GDP growth in Q2 of 2003, while  
the number in PRC was 4.75. As the virus keeps on spreading globally,  
many countries whose economic structure is highly based on the tourism  
industry. While a big portion of LEDCs, such as Vietnam and Bolivia, might  
pose a more serious impact, since income from tourists may take up an  
irreplaceable part of their national finance. This phenomenon could be  
observed, especially in Asian countries. The following figures would show  
the severity of the impact.  
Figure 2 shows a clear loss in 2003 for Malaysian tourism.  
Averaging 2002 and 2004 the loss estimate is RM 6425.15 million = US$ 1.7 billion.  
Figure 3: restaurants income sum in Hong Kong (unit: million HK dollars)  
However, it should also be noted that, in fact, the economic impact caused  
by SARS was not as devastating as many experts predicted during the  
pandemic. This is mainly because the seriousness of the disease and the  
number of confirmed cases werent threatening enough in many countries  
to make consumers significantly decrease their will of shopping. That is, the  
highly-influenced area was only confined to eastern Asia, as a result, the  
final outcome was more like a short-term severe regional economic crisis,  
instead of a global economic decay.  
Latest Developments  
Latest Developments on SDG No.4  
In 2020, as the COVID-19 pandemic spread across the globe, a majority of  
countries announced the temporary closure of schools, impacting more  
than 91 percent of students worldwide. By April 2020, close to 1.6 billion  
children and youth were out of school. And nearly 369 million children who  
rely on school meals needed to look to other sources for daily nutrition.  
In an effort to foster international collaboration and ensure that education  
never stops, UNESCO is m ounting a response with a set of initiatives that  
include the global monitoring of national and localized school closures  
.  
To protect the well-being of children and ensure they have access to  
continued learning, UNESCO in March 2020 launched the COVID-19  
Global Education Coalition, a multi-sector partnership between the UN  
family, civil society organizations, media, and IT partners to design and  
deploy innovative solutions. Together they help countries tackle content  
and connectivity gaps, and facilitate inclusive learning opportunities for  
children and youth during this period of sudden and unprecedented  
educational disruption.

Latest Developments on SDG No.8  
The COVID-19 pandemic has caused a historic recession with record  
levels of deprivation and unemployment, creating an unprecedented  
humanitarian crisis that is hitting the poorest hardest.  
In April 2020, the United Nations released a  
f ramework for the immediate  
socio-economic response to COVID-19, as a roadmap to support countries  
path to social and economic recovery. It calls for an extraordinary scale-up  
of international support and political commitment to ensure that people  
everywhere have access to essential services and social protection. The  
socio-economic response framework consists of five streams of work:  
1
2
3
. Ensuring that essential health services are still available and  
protecting health systems;  
. Helping people cope with adversity, through social protection and  
basic services;  
. Protecting jobs, supporting small and medium-sized enterprises, and  
informal sector workers through economic response and recovery  
programs;  
4
. Guiding the necessary surge in fiscal and financial stimulus to make  
macroeconomic policies work for the most vulnerable and  
strengthening multilateral and regional responses; and  
. Promoting social cohesion and investing in community-led resilience  
and response systems.

and gender equality imperative to build back better

Key Issues  
Capacity strengthening of LEDCs  
Less Economically Developed Country (LEDC) is a term to refer to  
thedeveloping countries." As for those developed countries, its usually  
called the More Economically Developed Countries(MEDC). Although  
there is no clear index to classify all UN Member States into LEDCs or  
MEDCs, the UN listed  
status would be updated every three years under the evaluation of the  
Committee for Development (CDP). According to the United Nations,  
4 8 Least Developed Countries in 2018, and the  
LEDCs are highly vulnerable to economic and environmental shocks and  
have low levels of human assets. Although the LEDCs have privileges to  
receive i nternational support from the United Nations, they are still required  
to reform the structure of their system in order to curb the gap attributed to  
globalization. In comparison with the MEDCs, the LEDCs possess several  
common points regarding work and education as follows:  
1
2
3
4
5
. Poor infrastructures;  
. Low GDP and Human Development Index (HDI);  
. High mortality rate and birth rate;  
. Low literacy rate;  
. Low minimum wage and poor working conditions.  
Those previously mentioned aspects render the issue harder to solve since  
we can not only consider the topic in a limited group (i.e. MEDCs);  
therefore, delegates should take this part into consideration while  
conducting research or drafting clauses.  
Slowbalization  
Globalization has been an unstoppable fad in the world for long. However,  
this phenomenon has become less significant recently. Many experts even  
believe that we have already experienced the peak of globalization and  
looking in the predictable future, the speed of globalization will turn into a  
 s nail's pace. Therefore, a new term, slowbalization was coined to  
describe this specific circumstance. Moreover, due to the eruption of  
COVID-19, the amount of international consumption and cross-border  
economical interaction has dropped dramatically. Recognizing that the  
economy of any country may be highly connected with each other, and that  
international division of labor has become a common way of managing the  
business, the situation of slowbalisation is a topic worth discussing.  
Unequal regional development  
Economists have indicated that the current outbreak of COVID-19 has  
made the poorest poorer. Without enough supplies and public health  
infrastructures, LEDCs struggle to react to the pandemic more than MEDCs  
do. Whats worse, a large number of people living in LEDCs rely on an  
informal economy empowered by tourists to make a living, which leaves  
them in an immediate threat of starving. As a result, assisting LEDCs on  
getting through and recovering from this crisis as well as balancing the  
division of resources between regions will be the aim of this committee.  
Unemployment  
The COVID-19 outbreak has brought a great decline in the amount of  
global trade, countless businesses, and factories are forced to shut down.  
The rate of unemployment is also rocketing under such circumstances.  
Therefore, governments are obliged to come up with methods to secure  
laborers rights.  
Global economical decay  
Both international and regional institutions should be responsible for public  
health, especially those in LEDCs, whose governments are often relatively  
lacking experience in reacting to crises. Therefore, its necessary for  
delegates to move on to the improvement and renovation of public health  
bureaus to prevent similar situations from happening again.  
Possible Solutions  
Construction of Decent Infrastructure  
Infrastructure is the foundation of a countrys prosperity and mobility while  
facing emergency issues. Under pandemic, people tend to keep in contact  
with each other via mobile devices and networks. This scheme could also  
work on both work and education. According to the British Broadcasting  
Corporation(BBC), ZOOM, an online meeting application, has been used  
for holding webinars and cross-government discussions. As for education,  
the prevalence of online tutoring and courses are attributed to quarantine.  
More people now in 2020 tend to receive education via the internet rather  
than that in the real world. Hence, the universalization of networking is  
crucial in order to face urgent issues as well as to keep up with the latest  
trend.  
However, on one hand, LEDC countries do not possess abundant  
constructions on base stations or networking services; on the other hand,  
the LEDCs may not have enough financial resources to afford the cost of  
those. Moreover, it is distinct that even some of the built ones lack quality  
and sustainability. Taking the transportation system in Africa as an  
example, the Tanzania-Zambia Railways (Tazara) in Africa, one of the  
significant regional railway systems, encounters several unexpected trials  
over four decades in operation since there are abandoned train wagons  
scattered on the track and some derailed sections are not well-maintained.  
Hence, less than 2% of the rail line's maximum capacity is being used.  
Most of the heavy cargos are transported by other means of transportation.  
In this case, Member States ought to link SDG Goal 9, 11 with capacity  
strengthening together, starting from the basis in order to construct a  
decent living place, therefore enhancing the stability of the country while  
facing unforeseen incidents.  
Adaptive Measures of Industries  
Given the differences among multiple industries, appropriate anti-epidemic  
measures should be provided based on categories. Technological  
industries or general businesses are able to process work online.  
Employees could avoid any possibility of virus infection during the period of  
working while ensuring their work can be done.  
On the other hand, the primary sector (i.e. labor-intensive industry) makes  
up the major portion of the economy in LEDCs; however, those industries  
are unable to work online. Therefore, it is more imperative to advocate the  
importance of wearing masks and social distancing in order to reduce  
contagious risk in these countries. Also, the authorities concerned can set  
up relevant penalties when necessary. In this case, its also important to  
promote the virus prevention materials such as masks and alcohol through  
multi-media which are recommended to call on the collaboration between  
governments and enterprises, in order to achieve the effect of producing  
enough epidemic prevention materials.  
Protection of Labors  
The Institute of Economic Opportunity and the National Labor Organization  
estimates that in the second quarter, working hours in the Americas were  
reduced by 12.4% (compared to pre-crisis levels), and by 11.8% in Europe  
and Central Asia. Aiming to this situation, the ILO has made a declaration,  
"The measures to restore the economy should take a heavy workload, and  
there should be stronger employment policies and systems, and a  
comprehensive social protection system with better resources.  
Coordination of international economic stimulus plans and debt relief  
measures It is also vital to making the recovery effective and sustainable."  
Hence, possible measures such as enabling a minimum wage guarantee  
should be well-concerned. Labors should be protected under stable wages  
given by employers.  
Educational Resource and Venue Safety Optimizing  
Owing to the lack of educational hardware in LEDCs, common means of  
preventing pandemic such as online learning may not be feasible to those  
countries. Hence, specialized and affordable solutions should be figured  
out and specified, such as advocating the importance of wearing masks in  
public occasions, enforcing regular handwashing in schools, promoting  
social distancing, fair distribution of medical supplies, etc. Delegates can go  
deeper on the way to implement those measures or concepts as well as to  
consult the feasibility of the scheme with other delegates.  
Worldwide Collaboration  
The construction of a better-living world requires joint efforts. In other  
words, a single nation can not accomplish these goals on its own, and all  
countries are obliged to shoulder the responsibility. While nations are  
mutually dealing with the enlightenment of labor rights or compulsory  
education, Member States spontaneously fulfill the goal of SDG Goal 17:  
partnership for the goals. Hence, several measures can be taken to bring  
about collective efforts in order to achieve the SDGs. Means such as but  
not limited to collaborating with numerous states on the foundation of  
bilateral interests, loaning from the World Bank or other UN-affiliated  
organizations, signing free-trade-area contracts (FTA) among countries,  
participating in regional forums or organizations such as the Association of  
Southeast Asian Nations(ASEAN) or African Union (AU) could be some of  
the remedies to tighten the bond among governments as well as to show  
how a country can be indispensable to the world.  
Questions to be considered  
1
. What preventive or proactive measures can be applied or adopted  
regarding the two SDGs this committee is discussing under  
COVID-19 in the country you represent?  
2. Are there any precedents (e.g. MERS in the Republic of Korea) to be  
considered? If so, how did your country deal with the issue? If not,  
are there any measures that the co u ntry you represent is facilitating  
under COVID-19?  
3
. How could the committee and the well-developed countries help the  
LEDCs to recover faster in the post-pandemic stage, as well the  
enhancement and acceleration on SDG 4 and 8 after the hampered  
progress due to the pandemic?  
4
. With non-binding resolutions in this committee, what kind of  
measures can be taken to ensure all member states on approving  
and having further cooperation?
